``` r
#Q2
covar= read_csv("nhanes_covar.csv", skip = 4) |>
  janitor::clean_names() |>
  mutate(age = as.integer(age)) |>
  mutate(sex = case_when(
    sex == 1 ~ "male",
    sex == 2 ~ "female"
  )) |>
  mutate(education = case_when(
    education == 1 ~ "<HS",
    education == 2 ~ "=HS",
    education == 3 ~ ">HS"
  )) |>
  mutate(education = as.factor(education)) |>
  filter(age>20) |>
  drop_na(sex, age)
```

``` r
ggplot(covar, aes(x = age, fill = sex)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ education) +
  labs(title = "Age Distribution by Gender and Education Level",
       x = "Age",
       y = "Count")
```

![](hw3sol_files/figure-gfm/unnamed-chunk-2-1.png)<!-- -->

Q- Produce a reader-friendly table for the number of men and women in
each education category, and create a visualization of the age
distributions for men and women in each education category. Comment on
these items. Ans- In the table we have created that shows the number of
men and women in each education category, we observe that the less than
high school and more than high school numbers are pretty similar for
both the sexes (slightly more females in both categories). However,
there is a significant difference in the number of men with high school
equivalent education than women. It is also important to note that in
our tidied dataset the number of men is more than the number of women
(120 vs 111). Through the visulisation we also see that there is one
outlier in the \>HS data where there are a lot of females at a certain
age.

accel = read_csv("nhanes_accel.csv") |>

  mutate(avg_activity = total_activity/1440)
